   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "969cbef7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Quick start guide\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7d207f40",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Overview\n",
    "\n",
    "Our goal with this quick start guide is to enable users to get good results on IBM Quantum systems with minimal effort and know-how.  In short, below outlines a good initial recipe for:\n",
    "\n",
    "1) Transpiling circuits\n",
    "\n",
    "2) Finding the best physical qubits to use on a target system\n",
    "\n",
    "3) Applying basic error suppression techniques\n",
    "\n",
    "4) Optionally, performing readout error mitigation\n",
    "\n",
    "By design this guide does not go into the why and how of each step, but rather just presents the recipes in such a manner that an interested user can copy and paste the code into their projects."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "0685eeae",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:36.393524Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:35.213836Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from qiskit import *\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import hellinger_fidelity\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "plt.style.use('ibmq-dark')\n",
    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "eea0fc45",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Frontmatter\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Here will will show the best current compiling strategy for generic circuits.  As a concrete example we will take a Bernstein-Vazarani circuit and map it onto a 27Q system.  We begin by grabbing the target backend:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "83843169",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:51.262806Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:36.395887Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "IBMQ.load_account()\n",
    "provider = IBMQ.get_provider(group='deployed')\n",
    "backend = provider.get_backend('ibm_geneva')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "44445646",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next we define our test circuit:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "0ce59193",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:51.968087Z",

    }

    "qc = QuantumCircuit(6, 5)\n",
    "qc.x(5)\n",
    "qc.h(range(6))\n",
    "qc.cx(range(5),5)\n",
    "qc.h(range(5))\n",
    "qc.measure(range(5), range(5))\n",
    "qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0a9e9fcd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Best transpiling strategy"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e75ac6a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As a general rule it is always best to use `optimization_level=3` in Qiskit.  This uses the best swap mapping algorithm, and includes additional gate optimizations that can further optimize your circuits.  Note that there is a bit of code included in `optimization_level=3` that turns on approximate gate synthesis that we do not want.  So also setting `approximation_degree=0` is good.  That is to say when transpiling your circuit(s) once you should do:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "835346fb",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:57.989848Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:51.970471Z"
    },
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1710.73x3455.48 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 2813,
       "width": 1400
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "trans_qc = transpile(qc, backend, optimization_level=3, approximation_degree=0)\n",
    "trans_qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "eb75caf5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "However, typically transpiling circuits in Qiskit once is not enough.  This is because the transpiler nominally has to add swap gates to map the circuit to the desired quantum hardware.  The methods by which the swaps are added is stochastic, leading to a variable number of cnot gates in the output circuit.  Because cnot gates are expensive in terms of error rates, we want the circuit with the fewest cnot gates possible.  This requires transpiling multiple times (~10 or more) and taking the one with the lowest cnot gate count.  For a single circuit this can be done as follows:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "0e020142",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:59.112892Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:57.991485Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Number of cnots: [20 14 14 17 11 11  8 11 12 14]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Transpile the circuit 'qc' 10 times\n",
    "trans_circ_list = transpile([qc]*10, backend, optimization_level=3, approximation_degree=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "# get the number of cnot gates\n",
    "cx_counts = np.asarray([circ.count_ops().get('cx', 0) for circ in trans_circ_list])\n",
    "print('Number of cnots:', cx_counts)\n",
    "\n",
    "# select the circuit with the loweest number\n",
    "best_idx = np.where(cx_counts == min(cx_counts))[0][0]\n",
    "best_trans_qc = trans_circ_list[best_idx]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "8248c6e9",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:01.170017Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:36:59.115102Z"
    },
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1710.73x3455.48 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 2820,
       "width": 1400
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "best_trans_qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a3ff553d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Find the best physical qubits\n",
    "\n",
    "Having found the circuit with the lowest number of cnot gates, we are now in a position to find the best (or nearly so) qubits on which to execute the circuit.  You might might be wondering why this step is needed given the the circuits above are already mapped onto qubits.  Well, this is because the choice of qubits used at `optimization_level=3` is selected to try to best minimize the number of added swap gates, but is chosen at random.  Given the variability of qubits and gates found on today's hardware, those qubits are likely not ideal.  So here we look for the best qubits using `mapomatic` and remap the circuit onto them. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "213a31a9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n",
    "If you do not have mapomatic installed, you can do so via:<font style=\"font-family:'Courier New'\"> pip install mapomatic</font>.\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "725c7294",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:01.176327Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:01.171855Z"
    },
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import mapomatic as mm"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "99bce398",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "First we need to reduce the size of our circuit (now at 27 qubits in width) down to just the active qubits used in the circuit:"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "d733469b",
   "metadata": {

    "Now we are going to find the best possible qubit selection for this circuit as determined by the calibrations:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "784a9dd3",
   "metadata": {

    "best_layout"

   "id": "f34cb75d",

    }

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "78d3ab54",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Simple error suppression\n",
    "\n",
    "Having now settled on a good set of qubits we can now apply dynamical decoupling (DD) to suppress some forms of errors.  Doing this requires a few additional imports.  Here we do a very simple DD gate (pulse) sequence of two X-gates."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "8207fdef",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.305127Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.302019Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from qiskit.circuit.library import XGate\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler import PassManager, InstructionDurations\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler.passes import ALAPScheduleAnalysis, PadDynamicalDecoupling"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8c25a566",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Because DD requires timing knowledge, we must get the duration of each operation that the backend supports."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "285cea52",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.313081Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.307492Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "durations = InstructionDurations.from_backend(backend)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "294aaf0f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We also need to get the timing constraints that tell us the limitations of the device:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "e86087a6",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.319114Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.315729Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "constraints = backend.configuration().timing_constraints"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bfaf76de",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally we have to get the timing information into the circuit and the DD gate sequences inserted into the idle times of the circuit:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "30d2f546",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:05.055806Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:03.321387Z"
    },
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1604.87x3455.48 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 14,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 2820,
       "width": 1314
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dd_sequence = [XGate(), XGate()]\n",
    "pm = PassManager([ALAPScheduleAnalysis(durations),\n",
    "                  PadDynamicalDecoupling(durations, dd_sequence, pulse_alignment=constraints['granularity'])])\n",
    "opt_qc = pm.run(best_qc)\n",
    "opt_qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "726f27af",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Readout error mitigation (optional)\n",
    "\n",
    "The basic circuit operations with the largest error rates on the IBM Quantum systems are measurements.  Given that microwave photons are some 5 orders of magnitude less energetic than their visible counterparts, this should not be surprising.  Luckily it is straightforward to reduce the impact of these errors through mitigation.  Here we will do so via M3."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "25ec9ded",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-07T22:40:09.105405Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-07T22:40:09.088388Z"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n",
    "If you do not have M3 installed, you can do so via:<font style=\"font-family:'Courier New'\"> pip install mthree</font>.\n",
    "</div>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "2deb63de",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:05.087078Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:05.057511Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import mthree"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e772c0e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The first thing that needs to be done is to determine which physical qubits in the device are being measured in the circuit.  This can be done using the `final_measurement_mapping` function that returns a dictionary of `physical qubit : classical bit` key-value pairs:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "95a8e964",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:05.092967Z",
     "start_time": "2022-07-08T01:37:05.088819Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{4: 0, 2: 1, 1: 2, 8: 3, 3: 4}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 16,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "measured_qubits = mthree.utils.final_measurement_mapping(opt_qc)\n",
    "measured_qubits"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "26e89355",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next we construct a M3 mitigation object, and then pass the `measured_qubits` to tell the object to calibrate those measurement values:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "ccaf6fb4",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {

   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "mit = mthree.M3Mitigation(backend)"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,

   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {

   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1b91f399",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, up until this point, we have yet to actually run our compiled and error suppressed circuit.  We will need the raw result to perform mitigation so lets run the circuit now:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "9f87a493",
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2022-07-08T01:39:05.616447Z",

    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "raw_counts = backend.run(opt_qc, shots=10000).result().get_counts()"

   "id": "7da4ac19",
   "metadata": {},

    "With this data in hand, we can now correct the returned distribution:"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "quasi = mit.apply_correction(raw_counts, measured_qubits)\n",
    "quasi"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6ef39505",
   "metadata": {

   "source": [
    "The above output may contain small negative values, indicating it is not a true probability distribution, bur rather is a **quasi-probability distribution**.  This is ok for computing expectation values that are at the heart of most near-term applications and algorithms.  For example, our above example ideally has an expectation value $\\langle ZZZZZ\\rangle=-1$.  The raw results yield:"
   ]

    "So we see that indeed, the readout error mitigation gives an improved expectation value.  It is important to note that this does come with an increase in the corresponding standard deviation, and thus one needs to execute more circuits to obtain a desired precision.\n",
